etropolis -- t49 On the Road in Olympic-Era Tokyo -- t50 Traversing Tokyo by Subway -- t51 The Uses of a Free Paper Map in the Internet Age -- t52 Tsukiji at the End of an Era -- tNew Directions in the Digital Age -- t53 Probabilistic Earthquake Hazard Maps -- t54 Citizens’ Radiation Mapping after the Tsunami -- t55 Run and Escape -- t56 Postmortem Cartography: “Stillbirths” and the Meiji State -- t57 Reconstructing Provincial Maps -- t58 The Art of Making Oversize Graphic Maps -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMiles of shelf space in contemporary Japanese bookstores and libraries are devoted to travel guides, walking maps, and topical atlases. Young Japanese children are taught how to properly map their classrooms and schoolgrounds. Elderly retirees pore over old castle plans and village cadasters. Pioneering surveyors are featured in popular television shows, and avid collectors covet exquisite scrolls depicting sea and land routes. Today, Japanese people are zealous producers and consumers of cartography, and maps are an integral part of daily life. But this was not always the case: a thousand years ago, maps were solely a privilege of the ruling elite in Japan. Only in the past four hundred years has Japanese cartography truly taken off, and between the dawn of Japan’s cartographic explosion and today, the nation’s society and landscape have undergone major transformations. At every point, maps have documented those monumental changes. Cartographic Japan offers a rich introduction to the resulting treasure trove, with close analysis of one hundred maps from the late 1500s to the present day, each one treated as a distinctive window onto Japan’s tumultuous history. Forty-seven distinguished contributors—hailing from Japan, North America, Europe, and Australia—uncover the meanings behind a key selection of these maps, situating them in historical context and explaining how they were made, read, and used at the time. With more than one hundred gorgeous full-color illustrations, Cartographic Japan offers an enlightening tour of Japan’s magnificent cartographic archive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCartographyzJapanvPictorial works. 0aCartographyzJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBernstein, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Mary Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBestor, Theodore C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotsman, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Philip C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrixler, Fabian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFedman, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiévé, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreedman, Alisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFumiko, Miyazaki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFumiko, Sugimoto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFumiko, Sugimoto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoree, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHein, Carola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenry, Todd A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJunko, Suzuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaracas, Cary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaracas, Ca